The more Irish people I meet the more I realise there's no such thing as an Irish accent - there are dozens of broad accents that are each unique.  Its as silly as saying an English accent - what do you mean, English?  Cornish?  Manc?  Cockney?  West Country?  Brummy?  Scouse?  Geordie? Poor Kerrywoman. Anglo-Irish people exist! I grew up with that sort of accent in the Maynooth/Celbridge/Straffan area. I absolutely believe she could be from Kerry, which would make it the accent of at least one Kerrywoman. But in any county the Anglo-Irish are a tiny minority and our accent doesn't really represent any part of Ireland. She sounds like she could be a member of my family. I know people from almost every county with that accent.  I grant you using a tiny minority accent isn't a great way to represent a whole county. But then again the Louth man doesn't have a typical Louth accent either, and the Northsider doesn't exactly sound like a Moore Street vendor or a Colm Meaney or any of the archetypical Northsiders I know. I think they just got a bunch of Irish people and listed their counties, without really asking if their accent is representative of that county.

rewatching this ages later because youtube decided to shove this onto my homepage again, and it killed me how instantly wrong but also not wrong the 'how to do an irish accent lady' was. like the general idea she had was correct when pronouncing I/ireland, but she kept closing the first vowel of the diphthong too much. it's far closer to the korean vowel eo than the closed lip oo sound she was making. once we got to 'flower' it fell apart completely LOL. she even contradicts herself immediately after the i/ireland diphthong mistake by doing that closed vowel at the start of the diphthong, but then correctly saying immediately after that vowels in irish english move from the back of the mouth to the front in a fluid motion, which means a dipthong isn't going to start with a closed vowel and then open. it will either start with an open vowel and close, or use exclusively closed or exclusively open vowels. this is a concept that carried over to the irish english dialect from the irish language.

Brad Pitt plays an Irish traveller in Snatch, not an Irish person. Theres a big difference between being an irish traveller and being Irish. The majority of Irish travellers in England/Scotland /Wales have never been to anywhere in Ireland let alone been born there. They speak with the accents they have because they dont really associate outside of their own families and community, and just pick up that accent from birth, so they tend to have an "irish" accent that you probably couldn't place it in actual Ireland/Northern Ireland. I come from irish grandparents on my dads side but my soeaking voice is 100% local to the town i live in in England. I have a friend though, who was born in England, but is from a traveller family, and he has a mainly irish sounding accent, and although he has visited Ireland once or twice in his life, his most recent family that came from ireland before him is a grandparent on one side, and 2 great grandparents on the other side. But everyone in his home life speaks pretty much the same as he does. They arent putting a fake irish accent on, its just their natural speaking accent.  And in regards to Snatch, to be honest although he might not sound irish, Brad Pitt sounds a hell of a lot like the irish travellers do. also, regarding my mate has the traveller accent at home, but then has a generic vaguely local English accent for when he's outside of his home life. He's multilingual and multiaccented. And hes also doing what a lot of the travelling community have started doing, whch they never used to, and putting down roots, buying a house and settling down locally here. So maybe traveller isn't the right word for him now.

The sheep farmer lives in an area in which the Irish (Gaelic) language has remained the first language, in the same clip you can hear his neighbours speaking Irish. He is difficult for many people to understand because unlike the majority of Irish people he has strong Gaelic influence on his English.   It is rare that people are exposed to the most diverse of Irish/Hiberno English dialects on the national (Dublin centric) television stations and it is quite sad that the reflex of many Irish young people is to laugh and make jokes about the way older people in particular areas speak. My fathers family are from Kerry, can understand the man perfectly and really don't understand the reaction to a dialect which to them growing up was not abnormal.

Ireland isn't really any different on the "accent" front in that there are multiple accents within Ireland...just as basically everywhere else.  It's always funny to me when someone does an "American accent"...like, which one? There are numerous *states* with multiple accents within...let alone the entire country lumped together as one. Like...listening to some people from parts of Baltimore then listening to someone from Bethesda...you'd never guess they were from the same state. California has like 5 accents, Texas has like 4, and Florida has about 3...and I'm only talking major differences here, if you did all of the subtleties, there'd be at least 1000 accents in the U.S. . In some cases, you can hear serious accentual differences within the same city...one of my professors was from Queens in NYC, and my grandfather is from Brooklyn...very different sound there.

Accents are just so fascinating! I love hearing all the different types of accents even just w/in a language. They have like, ten million different variations and quirks w/in a language (and esp when people are speaking other languages), even w/in cities, nvm whole countries. People like to rag on Americans being stereotypically stereotypical about other accents, but for ex, what's usually assumed to be the 'Boston accent' is actually a South Boston accent, kinda like how 'Cockney' is the accent originating in East London. Jesus. As someone who has been around Border Collies for many years, we hear some crazy Scottish accents, but I only caught about half of what that dude was saying about his missing sheep. We have some world-class sheepdog handlers come to trials over here, and it's fucking HILARIOUS to see them telling a story, and all the other people will be smiling and nodding, and as soon as the Scot walks away, everyone's like, "Did anyone catch any of that?" When I lived in Michigan, we would drive up to Kitchener, Ontario quite often. Kitchener has a LOT of Newfie's up there,.  I have never heard such a combination of accents in my life than listening to a gaggle of Newfies talking amongst themselves. Irish, Scottish, French, German were all heavily represented.   For such a sparsely populated area, the amount of dialects you hear is kind of mind boggling.   Still, hands down, the nicest people I've ever met. 5 minutes after meeting one, you're family, no questions asked.

In Sweden the accents and dialects depends on where you go. They're quite distinct a well. In Stockholm when you're ordering meatballs with ashed potatoes at a lunch restaurant they might ask: "Vill du ha lingon till det?" It translates to "Do you want lingonberries with that?". Honestly, the best source of learning an Irish accent Iâ€™ve found so far has been those â€œAccent Tagâ€ videos. Makes it a lot easier to hear what specific consonants and vowels are pronounced as, along with some small bit of general vocabulary.  The â€œthâ€ sounds stood out to me the most in those videos. â€œThâ€ at the end of the word tends to be shortened to just â€œtâ€ and â€œthâ€ in the middle of a word seems to fall somewhere between a â€œtâ€ and a â€œd.â€  Also, a lot of people try to put the stereotypical lilt in the wrong part of the sentence. Itâ€™s usually just at the end of the sentence, occasionally at the beginning but in a more subtle way.  Just an outsiderâ€™s perspective. :)

Disclaimer: I do not pretend to know the language or accents very well I believe I have an answer to why they refer to "your woman" as "your wan" Taking Duolingo lessons, I believe it comes from the word for "lady". Bhantierna. The "bh" here makes that W sound, so it's more like WAN-Teer-Nuh. Here's a little lifehack for doing a casual irish accent: start from a stereotypical pirate voice. The pirate "accent" tends to lean hard on Irish as a foundation since they say a lot of irish folk turned to piracy during that notable, brief golden age in history. And it tends to exaggerate the iconic bits because it's not tied to a country or culture that you might insult by going hard on the caricatures. Just make sure it's only the starting point, there's plenty of room for other accents in your standard silly pirate voice, so you need to know when to draw the line and start putting in more thought.

Growing up, I was obsessed with Ireland and it's traditions / cultural aspects [I still am honestly]. When I was younger, I learned from my grandparents [on my mother's side] that I had Irish in me [I don't know if it's like a small percentage or more, they didn't say] and it was one of the most exciting things to learn about myself. For some reason, I wanted to try and embrace that part of me by trying to be more irish and the first thing that came to mind was learn to speak with an Irish accent. So, I looked up a bunch of videos and stuff to learn how, but every time I tried to do it I felt like I was offending an entire country and it made me feel embarrassed by the thought. I mean, I'm somewhat learning still, but I've noticed that I tend to use one at random like when I hear someone else do it, my brain feels prompted to do it and before I even get a chance to stop myself I randomly start talking in that accent and it's so weird because my friends and family will look at my weird like, â€œWhere the fuck did that come from?â€  [Edit]: Apparently the when you randomly copy an accent it's called Unconscious Accent Mimicry or AKA The Chameleon Effect!

Some of these accents remind me of Newfoundland & Cape Breton, Nova Scotia (where there's lots of Irish ancestry). Apparently most of the Irish Immigrants who settled on Newfoundland came from Waterford, Kilkenny, Tipperary, Wexford, and Cork. I'm from South Shore Nova Scotia and tend to drop T's (or replace them with the 'sh' sound) and accentuate vowels and R's. Lots of German ancestry over here. 12:22 You know jack, it's actually the same with german langauge. Long tought and indulged american or english students practicing german, are horribly shocked when they realize, baverian german or austrian german, is not the same thing as standard German.  For example when they start living in munich.  Standard german speakers (born in states like the Northrine) have hughe difficulties of understanding  baverian (another dialect of  german speeach) language. So when ever a foreign student travels to baveria,  sufficiently versed in the standart german language, they will find themselves lost when talking to a native baverian in german. Luckily most can understand  you and respond in  "proper" german language.  They can understand you, but you can't understand them, unless they try to talk in standart german (which still has very strong accent in that case unless they in turn are well versed in it.)  It's practically a dual lingual issue.

Lowkey, this reminded me of my Physics professor. He was South Ireland born with a super heavy accent for his area, but I could typically understand him because my parents were weird and had me pretty cultured with a bunch of different shows and movies when I was a kid (I'm American). We were working on a different material instead of our predesigned plans for the day. Everyone knew he played golf and he was using golf, which I also play, as an example for something maybe 5 minutes before this section. As he was lecturing, he was not writing anything on the board and kept saying "par" and my brain did not process that he was talking about because I thought he was still talking about golf. Like maybe he had carried over the discussion from earlier. We get another 20 minutes into the lecture with everyone shooting me glances to help them because he had been going off about par for too long , so I raise my hand and I just go:   "Sir, why are we still going over par? I thought we finished the golf example?" He just stares at me.... "Par? NO... Pawr."  I blink a few times. "Yeah, par like the hole has 4 par and you get the ball in the cup in 4 strokes.". "NO. PAWR." I start to chuckle, "Par?" "PAWR." "Why don't you write it down sir?" "P O W E R." "Oh, power. Got it. So do you want to relate power to golf today or should everyone trash their notes and try again?" He dropped the marker and started laughing his butt off for 5 minutes.

WAAAAAAAY way back in 2002. I volunteered at a Girl Scout event in County Cork. The girl scouts had different stations with challenges that were spread out all over the place and they had to come find the stations by hiking about the area. The station I was running was set up along the roadside next to a beautiful farm. The guy in the "Mad Accent" video reminded me of the farmer (and family) I met there. Lovely farmer and his family, though as the farmer was talking to me (and I can follow accents pretty well for a Canadian - one of the Girl Scout leaders warned me the family's accent was very strong and she was struggling with it even though she was from Cork as well) and anyway the farmer came out of his home eventually and came to chat and check in on me, I just nodded and smiled and tried to make conversation as best as I could with the guy. Next thing I know (because I just kinda agreed with everything that he was talking about) I was herding his cattle with him to get them down the road and across to another field..... **sigh** My friends from Galway were much easier to understand! :D :D :D

I understand your pain. When I say I'm from New York, people want to know what borough I'm from and why I don't sound like I'm from New York. People automatically assume, when you say you are from New York, that you are from New York City. They totally forget there is a whole other part called, New York State. In fact, all the entire state of New York has several different accents and dialects. If you live in the east, you might say "pop." In the central part of the state, you might say, "soda." And, in the western side, you might say, "soda pop." )Just my own observation.) Pizza can also be called, "pizza", "pizza pie", or a "pie", depending on what part of the state you are from. I think it is quite interesting. And, it is always fun to visit another state, in America, and be told you have an accent. 8-)

Scottish and Irish do strange things with t's in words. In Irish like Jack says it turns into an sh sound but in Scottish we leave out t's entirely. Only shows up if it's at the begining of words. Scottish becomes sco-ish. And that happens with nearly all words with t's in it. Names included  Only very select words will have it forced. Like the band Metallica will have a t pronounced. You're right though as an American.... I can confirm that there is a shit ton of different accents here and especially like Appalachian and really deep South accents it can be hard to understand what the hell people are saying even though you're both from the same country. It's easy enough to learn like a general accent like there's a way of doing a southern draw. But where I'm from here in Colorado there's certain little tiny nuances that make it unique to our area of the US.. It's one thing to get a broad generalization of certain words but definitely not the be all or end all of an accent. To be honest you kind of have to spend a lot of time in a certain region of a country in order to even begin to crack the accents of that country.

The b an b was also very cheep at just around 350 euro for us both for the week. We drove all the way up from Dublin to the b and b and drove around Ireland. We walked up the cliffs, beautiful views. I'm waiting for the day Hollywood do a Movie in Ireland with actual Irish people. It would sound so much better, obviously, and if it's difficult to understand they can just put subtitles in it haha. I always hate it when I hear people do a Cork Accent. I don't speak that way at all hahaha. I admit I know a good few people that talk that way to be fair, which sometimes annoys me because I can't tell if that's how they talk, which is fine, or they are doing it on purpose just to sound cool with their friends. Some people might not get this but I heard of a few people who would speak prim and proper to their family when at home but as soon as they go out with their friends it goes from "Hi, Mom. How are you getting on? Will I run down to the shop and get some milk?" and as soon as they leave the house and are around friends its like they have a split personality and they talk like this with friends "Watz da stry Boi? Watz da crack wit u? Any sca? Nah Boi nutin hapnin wit me boi? Shes a dacent lookin Beuor over der boi? Yur wan over der look?" OMG!!! haha, nothing against them I just don't like people that force an accent. When I speak with people and say where I'm from in Cork they never believe me at first. Thy always say "You don't speak like someone from there? You pronounce your words more clearly and Don't act like people from there. You don't use as much slang". Don't get me wrong I love Irish slang but I just don't use certain ones which everyone is used to hearing. I hate the word Beuor, but I used to say Dacent a lot and my mom used to kill me for it. When I got older I realised it does sound stupid and silly alright. Dacent is slang for Decent if someone doesn't know. The one thing I'm trying to stop saying because I notice I say it a lot is "D'ya know what I mean Like? Translate to "Do you undertstand what I'm talking about/saying? I also say me instead of my a lot now due to the fact I was doing a course in college with people from all over the place and now working with a good mix of accnets that my own has nearly become a hybrid mix of them all haha.

One thing to note, Accents morph over time, at with the westernization/globalization of the world, all accents are slowly getting watered down.  So as much as Brad Pitt's accent might seem ridiculous now, you'll wanna compare his accent to the accents at the time (20+ years ago) and not what is current day.

I've tried committing to an Irish accent before but it certainly is tricky. I'm American and I want to become a voice actor as my career, so I always infatuate myself with different accents from around the world and since I have a bit of Irish blood in me, I always try and attempt the Irish accent to improve in that said accent. Since I now see that there, like in America, are different dialects in Ireland, it certainly makes for an interesting challenge to try and imitate the accent in different dialects within Ireland.  Of course, I don't wish to offend anyone by making a bad accent and seemingly mock people who have that accent.

Watching this reminds me of the moment I fully believed that I have Irish ancestors...   My mom ordered a pint of ice cream...  But she said "pint" with an Irish accent...  I had never heard her say that word before, so I thought she was joking...   But she had NO idea she was saying it with an accent...  Then the next time I went to visit my Grandma, I asked her to say it (without saying it myself, of course) and SHE did it too!!!  It's funny how heritage can show up in the weirdest places...   Unfortunately, now that I pointed it out, they no longer say it with an accent...   It's a shame...

I think translation would help... not that i've been struggling I got sensitive ears and even though I don't speak any 2nd language fluently I can tell languages pretty often by the sound of em!  e.g the chinese hold on their vowels and the japanese like to have every syllable the same length when they speak, I can finally tell the difference between north and south korean aswell now even if I can't tell what they're saying...   then theres the instinct we all have body language and face expressions are almost universal so it's a good thing to learn cause even if something isn't translated you can get the gist of whats happening  as for west european accents I think ireland and england have way too many theres some english accents I can't understand so I think people focus on the popular ones that tend to sound like clear English and forget theres accents here that sound like a completely different language but are still considered an english accent!, and that's before you consider regional words that are just a local word but don't exist in the rest of the country!

I'm from Cornwall (I don't have a Cornish accent, other than occasionally rolling my r's) and we get cross when people people mix up Westcountry accents, so I can sympathize when people deciding that there's one Irish accent and and every person with an Irish accent just spins around and insults them with the particular Irish dialect that is only found in the wee, small corner of the Emerald Isle that their accent comes from. It's like people saying "I can do an English accent" and what they mean is they can do a bad home-counties accent.  There are so many bloody English accents.  So many!  If they could actually do an English accent then they would be attempting to do a Dudley accent - an accent so maligned that even people from Dudley 'extract the michael' for sounding like they do.  But it's much more representational of a proper English accent than trying to sound like the Queen or trying to sound like a Cockney.  After all, the sheer amusement of my little niece asking for a 'hook' when she really wanted a cuddle just goes to show that the Cheshire accent is not without its quirks and that's true for any accent in Northern Ireland and in Great Britain.

) A group of 119 Israelis, including 30 professors, 25 rabbis, and around 20 medical doctors and scholars, recently signed an open letter to the new Israeli Health Minister, Yuli Edelstein.  Among the signatories are former Deputy Speaker of the Knesset Mr. Moshe Feiglin; former Knesset member Mr. Yehudah Glick; Prof. Jacob Lavee, who has been leading efforts to stop the Chinese Communist Partyâ€™s killing of Falun Dafa practitioners for organs in China; and chief rabbis of several cities and communities in Israel.  The letter calls on the Minister of Health to examine and immediately stop all cooperation between Israel and China in the field of organ transplantation. This includes preventing Chinese physicians from training and attending professional conferences in Israel, as well as stopping all cooperation in research and development between the two countries in the face of the Chinese regime's forced organ harvesting of prisoners of conscience.  The signatories believe that a law should be enacted immediately to impose criminal liability on all forms of cooperation with Chinese entities on organ transplantation, including by private Israeli companies.  In addition, the signatories asked the Minister of Health to stop direct and indirect transmission of Israeli citizensâ€™ genetic information to Chinese state-owned companies. Furthermore, the signatories call for immediate action to end Israelâ€™s dependence on Chinese medical equipment and to re-examine the need for, and moral justification of, existing â€œtwin hospitalâ€ agreements between Israeli and Chinese hospitals.  Two Israeli media outlets covered the issue: a radio station interviewed one of the signatories, and an online Russian TV station interviewed the petitionâ€™s initiator.  The petition was submitted to the Ministry of Health at the end of May, but no reply has been received so far.   The project was started by an Israeli Falun Dafa practitioner, who suggests that practitioners in other countries consider taking similar initiatives.

I loved this video!
I have never been to Ireland, and my immediate family are not from Ireland. I was born in Plymouth, and was raised in Cornwall. O'Shannon isn't my original last name, I changed it when I started transitioning, and I picked it because it is the original form of my family name (Cannon), and it went better with what I chose as a first name. My first name was originally "Tristan", which for those who know Cornish/Irish folklore, the reason for my choice of first name should be obvious.  I was going to use the spelling "Iseult" but felt that people would struggle with that, so went for the spelling "Isolde" which people still have difficulty with.  I never ended up with a Westcountry accent, unlike the rest of my family, it has always been rather neutral. I can't even fake the accent from where I grew up. Funny thing is though, whenever I have had a few drinks, my accent has always changed to "some sort of Irish", not put on, I just fall into it. After watching this, I was curious what some of the other regional accents sound like, so looked at a few other videos.  The accent I seem to drop into sounds very much like County Clare.  I have always found it strange that my accent changes like that, when I have never been exposed to it.

There is a little Celtic shop in Pennsylvania where I live called "Oxford Hall". There is mostly Irish stuff there and Scottish as well, but there is some English too. I bought a hat there not to long ago that was hand crafted in Ireland which is pretty cool in my opinion. They sell tea and some "classics" in food choices and play the (sort of) stereotypical "Irish Music" non-stop. The man who owns it is always at the front check-out counter and is super nice and has been to Ireland multiple times. He has never had anything bad to say about it, so y'all must be doing something right (LOL). Overall it is a pretty quaint little shop. I like it.

After watching this video I feel like I can hardly speak right anymore. I'm from the state of Georgia, so I already have a southern accent going on, but after watching this I feel like the southern has increased and that has mixed with me unintentionally doing an Irish accent of some sort and it's weird. (Update: that didn't last very long but my was it an experience).  Like our man Sean has said, there are many dialects. Within' the American accent there's Southern, and within Southern there's Georgian, and within Georgian there's the ones in different cities, and I'm sure that can be divided up into more. I never really noticed different accents in my state before this one field trip in 8th grade that lasted maybe 2 or 3 days. Kids from different cities were at this one place with my school, and these kids from Atlanta said we (coastal Georgians) talked funny. We were really confused 'cause we thought they were the funny speakin' ones.  Anyways, I'd never think the Irish accent to be sexy. In general, I don't believe I've ever considered an accent to be sexy. I guess the closest an accent would be to sexy for me is Southern. As we established I'm Southern myself so I guess it's kinda weird to be attracted to accent in the same group as mine, but If you know me, you know I have a thing for cowboy men (I love them and wish to be one). McCree from Overwatch and Arthur from RDR2 yes pls. That's the only accent I think I can consider kinda sexy. I think a better word here would be attractive. I feel like I'd apply sexy only to voices, and even then I think of accents and voices on more on a coolness scale, which is basically how much I want the voice/accent for myself. Accents I find cool are , Irish, Scottish, and Australian in general since I can't name ones of specific areas in their respective countries.  (P.S. Sorry If this isn't understandable. I'm not very good with words.)

I have my own experience with incomprehensible Irish accents.  I live near Newry, which is the closest city to the Northern/Republic border. So you have the Ulster Brogue from some people in the city or those who come down to Newry to do some shopping since it has 2 shopping centres... or those from across or near the border who have the thickest fucking accents.  I did a work entry course via the Clanrye Group (wonderful people who run the course and they got me into work) and the bus driver was from across the border and sounded just like a Hollywood leprechaun. Also did a work experience in a shop in town and had to day that I couldn't understand a farmer due to how thick his accent was.

I have a friend from Galway who taught me about the notoriety of Limerick  Also I can empathize with you on feeling alone from being away from where you love. I was an exchange student in Japan for a year, and while I felt alone in my thoughts not being able to communicate, once I broke that barrier and could speak more freely, I felt more free than I ever have. I loved speaking the language and figuring things out whenever I was stuck on a word, and being able to rebuild myself where no one knew me was a liberating experience.  I truly loved being there, and being back home brought back the same pressure and depression I always lived with before. I'll be going back after College, but it's a hard feeling to work with.

The lady teaching the Irish accent sounds a lot more like a Newfoundland (in Canada) accent
What's really interesting is that I can hear the influence on the accent in my city Pittsburgh. Our accent and slang is influenced by scotch Irish, Pennsylvania Dutch (ie German spoken by Amish and Mennonites), and Eastern European like Polish, Russian, and Hungarian. I think the Irish shows in how we say, or rather don't say, the th sound. Like we'll refer to our city as "Da 'Burgh" or totally omit it in the case of the phrase "'n' 'at" (and that). I also find myself saying f instead of th lime in funk for think but I'm not sure if it's accent or mild speech impediment. Also we mush up our words-  iron is arn (1 syllable) and when I say Irish it can come out as Arsh, again just one syllable.   This could also be due to the other influences on our accent, but the similarities in this video were interesting.

17:48 "Yer wan" (meaning "that woman" in Irish slang) is possibly a shorthand for "your woman". I couldn't find any sources for its origin, but my best guess is that it initially referred to a female partner ("your wife", "your girlfriend") and then eventually was generalized for any woman. Something similar applies to "yer man" (meaning "that man" in Irish slang).

Heads up. I'm not sure you want to be focussing on your subscriber to non-subscriber rate. If your viewers were 100% subscribers you probably wouldn't be getting any new viewers (as none of your audience would be non-subscribers) and therefore no one to become new subscribers. How many are converting to subscribers over time might be a better metric. The Kerry Irish accent sounds a lot like the Hoi Toid accent from the outer banks of North Carolina. It is Elizabethan English with some Irish and Scottish tones mixed in. These kinds of accents exist due to very little outside influence. In the case of Hoi Toid, these were fishing villages who weren't really visited by outsiders until the 20th century. I have a feeling Kerry is mainly farming communities that stay relatively isolated. Both of these accents will eventually die out due to the exposure of the modern world.

When Americans think of an Irish Accent, we're thinking of Northside Dublin. I will say several years ago I was traveling home from a conference in London, and I had an 11 hour layover in Dublin, and me and many other people just waited in the Airport Lounge for it to open back up, and there was an Indian man working the bar, and I could not for the life of me understand a word he said as he had a super thick combination Irish-Indian accent.  After watching this though... It might have just been full blow Irish.  Because I also remember this red headed woman walk into the airport with 7 red headed kids, and I remember thinking "That's clearly a good catholic lady" but I couldn't understand a single word she was screaming at her kids.  I knew she was screaming in English... but I just couldn't make it out as she berated each kid, and then her youngest was rolling on the floor and she went all in dragging him up and was shouting more unintelligible words. That layover was practically a weird Irish fever dream.

The funny thing about how Irish people sound when they speak English - our accents come from how we would have sounded when speaking in Irish, (with regional dialects and stuff) if the majority of us still spoke Irish. For example, the â€œshhâ€ sound in the Kerry accent is still there when a Kerry person speaks in Irish and the broad, almost nasal sounds of the northern accent (frostbite guy) are still there in the northern Irish accent too. And then the accents just loose the plot all together when you meet actual native Irish speakers, for whom Irish is their first language. Itâ€™s gas altogether.

Me and my mum's side of the family are all from rural Galway (literally in the backend of NOWHERE, sheep everywhere, barely any shops, fields all around, everyone has a collie, nobody had internet until like last year). My grandad had the STRONGEST ACCENT IMAGINABLE because he was like... A proper old Irish farmer (like owned a lot of land and livestock, owned prized horses that were trained for professional horseracing, owned an old castle at one point, drowned kittens and puppies because they had no access to vets). For my whole life, I don't think I understood a single word he said, and I always had to get my mum to translate anything he said to me even though he was SPEAKING ENGLISH. It was absolutely wild.  Fun fact also: my grandad survived carbon monoxide poisoning, getting hit by vehicles like 6 times, 4 house fires, 2 heart attacks, being kicked by horses countless times, electrocution, various other near death experiences, and was also HELD AT GUNPOINT in a bar he owned and walked up and fuckin TOOK THE GUN OFF THE GUY saving like a HUNDRED people in the bar. He was an amazing man)

Alright that "how to do an Irish accent" video, she wasn't "wrong" but also very much wasn't "right"  Each vowel sound sounds slightly different depending on where you are in Ireland, so it's reeeeeally hard to fake the accent without actually having been there. (true for a lot of places in the world but idk where else has so much diversity) The point is if you learn one vowel sound wrong, maybe you make the "oi" sound too strong, it'll show every time you talk and it's really obvious. (Saying "oi" as in oil is a terrible way to describe how to say it, but I don't have a more accurate description that's short enough so I guess it's hard to blame anyone for it.)  I have a friend who moved to the USA, (I forget which state, somewhere on the west side) and he's been there for a while. Now he actually sounds like an American who's trying to sound Irish.

The reason Hollywood didn't do the smart thing and hire Irish actors is that they wanted to get Americans to see the movie by using famous American names. By casting people that the American public is already familiar with people will be more likely to see just to see the celebrity  (in Hollywoods pov). It's the same reason why so many animated movies include celebrity actors instead of voice actors, to appeal to the adults who see the names and go "I know this guy" and watch it with their kids. They do this just for celebrity endorsement (marketing) over accuracy.

One time, while working in a restaurant, I had a couple ladies ask what part of Ireland I am from. Now, I've lived 100% of my life in the United States, and my Great-Grandfather was born in Dublin for my closest to being from there. I apparently have a very subtle "Irish" hint when I talk according to them, but unless I'm consciously trying to do that "Lucky Charms Irish" accent, I honestly do not hear it. 4:50 I actually had an Irish teacher in English class (oral practice more specifically) and she shew us this video and said it was okay to have an accent as long as we are more understandable than this guy ğŸ˜‚  We then had to talk by pairs and she saw I was alone so instead of creating a group of three she decided to talk with me for a couple minutes and she said I had a good English (even though I know it's not quite true, because I'm always babbling anxiously which can make it hard to understand me).  The next year I had her as a teacher again in a subject where we had to discuss the adaptation of an English work into a movie and make a presentation about it. And instead of imposing us to work on specific movies her colleagues had chosen she let us choose our own adaptations and everyone was really happy about it.  I did a presentation about the adaptation of the comics Watchmen and (since it was during quarantine) I recorded myself, except I was really anxious and found myself out of breath so I had a hard time speaking and was making quite a lot of mistakes. So I sent it to her and told her she might have a hard time understanding me, but she took the time to respond to me and said she had listened to it and it was fine.  She really is a super nice teacher and everyone loves her which is why I often catch myself thinking Irish people must be really nice seeing how she and SeÃ¡n are such nice people.

My favorite thing about Brad Pitt's accent in Snatch, is that it's purposefully indecipherable for audience and characters alike. Guy Ritchie caught flak from Lock, Stock, and Two Smokin' Barrels from characters having accents that were hard to understand. So he made Pitt's accent ridiculous and impossible to understand to sort of poke fun at critics, and yet, critics thought it was pretty spot on.

You should judge accents from all over the world-
As an American who studied an Irish accent professionally (I was cast as Johnnypateenmike in a stage production of Martin McDonagh's "The Cripple of Inishmaan") I can confirm that it is a devilishly tricky accent to learn. I had a dialect coach, and I listened to multiple accents over the course of a couple of months (including some of the videos that SÃ©an showcased) to get my County Galway accent _just so,_ and even then I knew it wasn't perfect. It's been a few years since that play now, and it got decent reviews, but I doubt I could still render that accent correctly, not having practiced it in that time. It would take me about a month to get it back. Irish accents are not easy, so please, cast an Irish actor instead of an American one.

For some reason I have an obsession with all the Irish accents...
Once upon a time, because I was a big fan of an actor with a thick Northern Irish accent I'd grown very accustomed to Northern Irish accents. In his acting roles he never used his own accent though, I got used to it cause I would watch all of his interviews. Then he acted in a movie and I found out he was playing an Irish character from Dublin, so he would still not be using his own accent but I was like "oh okay it'll be fine I can understand his accent, surely it won't be that difficult for me to understand his character's accent". Maaan was I wrong. I start watching the movie, his character shows up and literally the very first thing he says is so unintelligible to me that I replay it for maybe 10 times, not being able to even take a guess at what he might be saying, and I give up watching the movie until I can find it with subs a whole freaking year later. I can still remember the sentence cause it left such an impression ahaha. I think over the years of watching Jack I have grown much more accustomed to Southern Irish accents though, I was able to understand some parts in this video, so I want to go back and rewatch that movie again sometime, to see if I've acquired the ability to understand his accent after almost 10 years ahaha
